<TITLE> Truckers' strike cripples business at Pakistan port </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KARACHI, Aug 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Truck drivers have gone on strike over high fuel costs at Pakistan's main port, virtually freezing business, traders said on Saturday. Traders estimate millions of dollars worth of perishable goods have been stranded by the strike. "The situation is very serious. I can tell you I have commitments to export 30 million rupees ($392,000) of rice this month to UAE," said a trader who declined to be identified. "I just can't do it because no truck is available to carry the rice from the warehouse to the port." Protesting drivers have put up picket lines on roads around the port and are not letting trucks through, traders said. Drivers' associations demand the government bring down the price of diesel. "We will continue our strike until the demands are met. It is difficult to bear the expenses. It's impossible," said Noor Khan Niazi, president of the Karachi Goods Carriers' Association. The government has been cutting subsidies on fuel as it struggles with widening budget deficits and inflation at a 30-year high
